In the village of Veythar, where the wind carried secrets like pollen, there stood an ancient oak called *The Witness*. Its bark was etched with names—some glowing faintly, others darkened by time. None knew who carved them, but all knew the truth: the tree held the *Unseen Ledger*, a record of every deed, spoken or unseen.

Young Kael, a hunter of sharp eyes and sharper tongue, scoffed at the legend. One evening, after feasting on stolen honey from old Maren’s hives, he boasted to his friends, ‘Who will know? The bees won’t tell.’ But the next dawn, Maren’s name on *The Witness* dimmed, and Kael’s brightened—though no one had seen him take the honey.

Word spread like wildfire. ‘Kael’s name shines,’ whispered the baker. ‘He must have done something noble,’ murmured the weaver. Kael, flattered, lied again—this time about slaying a wolf (though the beast still prowled the woods). The Ledger darkened further. His friends, once eager to hear his tales, now averted their eyes.

Years passed. Kael, now a lonely man, realized too late: the Ledger was not just wood and wind, but the *memory of the village itself*. When he finally confessed his thefts, the elders did not punish him—they *forgot*. His name faded from *The Witness*, as if it had never been. But the pattern endured: in Veythar, honor was not given, but *remembered*. And gossip, once spoken, became truth.

To this day, children are warned: *‘The tree hears all. The wind repeats all. Choose your words—and your deeds—as if the Ledger were carved in stone.’*"
