In the high valley of **Duskrend**, where the cliffs echoed like hollow drums, there stood a single black stone called *The Witness*. It was said the stone remembered every word spoken in its shadow—not just the lies, but the *truths left unspoken*. The villagers of Duskrend knew this: if you whispered a secret near *The Witness*, it would repeat it back to the wind. Not in your voice, but in the voice of the one you’d wronged.

Young **Taren**, a shepherd with a silver tongue, laughed at the old tales. ‘A stone cannot judge,’ he scoffed, as he led his flock past it one evening. That night, he stole a lamb from old **Hilda’s** pen, telling himself, *‘She has enough. No one will know.’* But the next morning, as Taren herded his sheep, the stone *spoke*—not to him, but to Hilda. Her voice, dry as dead leaves, carried on the wind: *‘Taren took what was not his. The stone heard.’*

The village turned. Not in anger, but in *knowing*. No one accused him. No one demanded the lamb back. They simply… *remembered*. When Taren tried to sell his wool at market, the weaver shook her head. When he asked for ale at the tavern, the keeper poured him water. His friends no longer laughed at his jokes. The stone had not punished him—it had only *told the truth*, and the truth, once spoken, could not be unsaid.

Years later, Taren, now an old man, returned to the stone. He placed a hand on its surface and whispered, *‘I am sorry.’* The wind carried no answer. But that winter, when a traveler asked why Taren’s name was never spoken in Duskrend, the villagers only said, *‘Some debts are carved in stone. Some are carved in silence.’*
